item.description:
Building read-heavy APIs? Don't let your ORM do unnecessary work. By default, `@Transactional` implies a write-capable session. For operations that only fetch data, you're paying for dirty checking and other write-related overhead you simply don't need.

Marking your service methods with `@Transactional(readOnly = true)` tells Spring and your JPA provider (like Hibernate) that the session is strictly for reads. This allows Hibernate to perform critical optimizations: it won't flush changes to the database, won't hold onto entities for dirty checking and can potentially use a read-only JDBC connection if configured.

It's a small change with a noticeable performance gain, especially under heavy load.

```java
@Service
public class ProductService {

    @Transactional(readOnly = true)
    public List<ProductDTO> getAllProducts() {
        // Fetch products, map to DTOs
        return productRepository.findAll().stream()
               .map(ProductDTO::fromEntity)
               .toList();
    }

    @Transactional
    public Product createProduct(Product product) {
        // Persist new product
        return productRepository.save(product);
    }
}
```

This simple tweak keeps your read paths lean and efficient.

You're building an API that needs to hit multiple external services or do heavy computation. If you're doing this sequentially within a single request thread, you're blocking your web server and wasting resources. Your API latency shoots up and throughput plummets.

Instead, embrace asynchronous processing with `CompletableFuture`. Wrap those long-running operations in `CompletableFuture` and let your web thread return immediately, processing other requests. When all async tasks complete, assemble the results.

Here's how a Spring `RestController` might use it:

```java
@GetMapping("/data")
public CompletableFuture<DataAggregate> getData() {
    CompletableFuture<String> userDetails = userService.fetchUserDetails();
    CompletableFuture<List<Item>> inventoryItems = inventoryService.fetchItems();

    return CompletableFuture.allOf(userDetails, inventoryItems)
            .thenApply(ignored -> {
                String user = userDetails.join();
                List<Item> items = inventoryItems.join();
                return new DataAggregate(user, items);
            });
}
```

Remember to configure a dedicated `ThreadPoolExecutor` for these async tasks to prevent thread pool exhaustion and fine-tune your concurrency. Your API will thank you with improved responsiveness and higher throughput.

When building relationships in JPA, how do you link a child entity to an existing parent without needlessly hitting the database for the parent's full data? Don't reach for `findById` if you only have the parent's ID.

`repository.findById(id)` *always* fetches the entity from the database. If you just need to set a foreign key, like when creating a `LineItem` and linking it to an `Order`, this is an unnecessary read.

Instead, use `repository.getReferenceById(id)`. This method returns a proxy object, an entity reference, without executing a SELECT query. The database is only hit if you access a field on that proxy *other than its ID*.

```java
// Assuming Order exists with ID 123
Order orderRef = orderRepository.getReferenceById(123L);

LineItem newItem = new LineItem();
newItem.setName("Awesome Widget");
newItem.setPrice(BigDecimal.valueOf(29.99));
newItem.setOrder(orderRef); // Associates without loading the full Order entity

lineItemRepository.save(newItem); // Only now is the Order ID part of the INSERT
```

This tiny optimization significantly reduces redundant queries and improves performance in high-volume write operations. Keep your database calls lean.

Still using `RestTemplate` for external API calls in your Spring Boot app? You're likely blocking threads unnecessarily. When a thread waits for an external service, it's idle but held, limiting your concurrency.

Switch to `WebClient`. It leverages non-blocking reactive streams, freeing your threads immediately after making a request. This significantly improves throughput under load, especially in microservice architectures where services call each other frequently.

Here's a quick example:

```java
import org.springframework.web.reactive.function.client.WebClient;
import reactor.core.publisher.Mono;

// In a service class
public Mono<SomeResponse> getExternalData(String id) {
    WebClient client = WebClient.create("http://external-service.com");
    return client.get()
                 .uri("/api/data/{id}", id)
                 .retrieve()
                 .bodyToMono(SomeResponse.class);
}
```

By returning a `Mono` or `Flux`, you're telling Spring and Reactor "I'll get this data eventually, but don't wait on me." Your application can handle more requests with the same resources. It's a game-changer for API performance.

Ever found yourself fetching a full entity from the database just to check if it exists? You might do `userRepository.findById(id).isPresent()` to confirm. While this works, it often pulls the entire row from your database, maps it to an object and then you just discard most of that work. That's a performance hit we can avoid.

When your sole purpose is to verify an entity's existence, `JpaRepository` provides a more efficient method: `existsById(ID id)`.

```java
// Avoid this for existence checks:
// Optional<User> user = userRepository.findById(userId);
// if (user.isPresent()) { /* ... */ }

// Do this instead for better performance:
if (userRepository.existsById(userId)) {
    // User exists, now proceed or fetch if actually needed later
    System.out.println("User confirmed to exist.");
} else {
    throw new UserNotFoundException("User not found: " + userId);
}
```

This `existsById` call translates to a `SELECT COUNT(*)` query at the database level, which is significantly lighter than a full `SELECT *`. It reduces data transfer, object creation and database load, making your APIs snappier. Small change, big impact.

You build APIs. Many fetch data that doesn't change every microsecond. Hitting the database for every request is often a performance bottleneck and a waste of resources. This is where Redis caching becomes your best friend. Spring Boot makes it ridiculously easy.

First, enable caching with `@EnableCaching` on your main application class. Then, for any method whose return value you want to cache, just slap on `@Cacheable`.

```java
@Service
public class ProductService {

    @Cacheable(value = "products", key = "#productId")
    public Product getProductDetails(Long productId) {
        // Simulating a costly database fetch
        System.out.println("Fetching product from DB for ID: " + productId);
        try { Thread.sleep(400); } catch (InterruptedException e) {}
        return new Product(productId, "Awesome Gadget " + productId);
    }
}
```

The first time `getProductDetails(1)` is called, your service logic executes and the result is stored in the `products` cache. Any subsequent calls for `getProductDetails(1)` will retrieve the `Product` directly from Redis, completely bypassing your service method. Remember to configure Redis in `application.properties`. It's a fundamental move for scalable backend systems.

Don't let your database be the bottleneck for frequently accessed data. If your Spring Boot API constantly fetches "hot" information like product catalogs or popular articles from PostgreSQL, you're needlessly burning resources. Caching is your immediate win here.

Spring's `@Cacheable` annotation provides a powerful, declarative way to cache method results. Pair it with Redis as your distributed cache store and watch your API performance soar.

```java
@Service
public class ProductService {

    private final ProductRepository productRepository;

    public ProductService(ProductRepository productRepository) {
        this.productRepository = productRepository;
    }

    @Cacheable(value = "products", key = "#categoryId")
    public List<Product> getProductsByCategory(Long categoryId) {
        // This line only executes if cache misses
        System.out.println("Fetching products from DB for category: " + categoryId);
        return productRepository.findByCategoryId(categoryId);
    }
}
```

With a properly configured `RedisCacheManager` in Spring, this simple annotation ensures `getProductsByCategory` executes its logic only once per `categoryId` until the cache expires. Subsequent calls retrieve data directly from Redis, drastically cutting database load and shaving milliseconds off your response times. Efficient and effective.
